<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 2 — Argument Structure and Reconstruction
  First full draft.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-argument-structure">

  <title>Argument Structure and Reconstruction</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-argument-structure-intro">
    <p>
      Chapter 1 taught us how to recognize arguments. That is already
      a real skill. Ordinary writing does not arrive with labels saying
      <q>premise here</q> and <q>conclusion here.</q> It arrives as
      paragraphs, conversations, editorials, policy memos, posts, essays,
      speeches, and half-remembered things people say after dinner.
    </p>
    <p>
      This chapter teaches the next skill: <term>argument reconstruction</term>.
      To reconstruct an argument is to take argumentative prose and lay
      out its structure clearly. We identify what the arguer is trying
      to get us to accept, which claims are supposed to support it, which
      claims are background or decoration, and how the pieces of support
      fit together. This work is slow at first, but it is the work that
      makes everything else in logic possible. We cannot ask whether an
      argument is valid, sound, strong, weak, fallacious, or persuasive
      until we know what argument we are actually evaluating.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-reconstruction-standard-form">
    <title>From Standard Form to Reconstruction</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Standard form is the simple layout introduced in Chapter 1:
        one statement per line, premises labeled P1, P2, P3, and a
        conclusion labeled C. Reconstruction begins there, but it is
        more than copying sentences into a list.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-reconstruction-is-cleanup">
      <title>Reconstruction is a cleaned-up representation</title>
      <p>
        A passage can contain an argument without being written like one.
        The conclusion may come first. A premise may be phrased as a
        rhetorical question. The author may repeat herself, add jokes,
        give background, or state an important assumption without spelling
        out exactly how it supports the conclusion. A reconstruction
        translates that mess into a clearer form.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-argument-reconstruction">
        <statement>
          <p>
            An <term>argument reconstruction</term> is a cleaned-up
            representation of an argument that identifies its premises,
            conclusion or conclusions, and support relations.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        The word <q>cleaned-up</q> matters. A reconstruction is not a
        transcript. We are allowed to remove clutter, standardize wording,
        and make the support relations explicit. But cleaned-up does not
        mean rewritten into the argument we wish the author had given.
        The goal is to represent the author's reasoning fairly.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-charity">
      <title>The principle of charity</title>
      <p>
        The guiding norm is often called the <term>principle of charity</term>.
        Interpret an argument in the strongest reasonable way. This does
        not mean pretending bad arguments are good. It means avoiding
        cheap victories that come from reading the arguer carelessly.
        If a sentence is ambiguous, choose the interpretation that best
        fits the surrounding passage. If the wording is sloppy but the
        intended claim is clear, repair the wording. If a modest unstated
        assumption is obviously doing work, make it explicit.
      </p>
      <p>
        Charity has limits. You should not invent a new argument and hand
        it to the author. If the missing assumption is enormous, contested,
        or not something the author seems committed to, note the problem
        rather than quietly adding it. Reconstruction is fair-minded, not
        magical.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <example xml:id="ex-voting-rule-reconstruction">
      <title>A first reconstruction</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider this passage:
        </p>
        <p>
          <q>If a rule prevents eligible citizens from voting without a
          strong public reason, then the rule should be repealed. This
          rule prevents eligible citizens from voting without a strong
          public reason. So this rule should be repealed.</q>
        </p>
        <p>
          A reasonable reconstruction:
        </p>
        <p>
          P1: If a rule prevents eligible citizens from voting without a
          strong public reason, then the rule should be repealed.
        </p>
        <p>
          P2: This rule prevents eligible citizens from voting without a
          strong public reason.
        </p>
        <p>
          C: This rule should be repealed. (from P1 and P2, which are
          dependent)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      Notice two things. First, the reconstruction does not add a separate
      line called <q>the argument.</q> The argument is the premises and
      conclusion together. Second, the parenthetical note after the
      conclusion tells us how the support works. P1 and P2 are dependent.
      P1 alone only states a general principle about rules that prevent
      eligible citizens from voting. P2 alone only says that this
      particular rule has that feature. Each premise gives much weaker
      support without the other; together, they give the reason for the
      conclusion.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-include-omit">
    <title>What to Include, What to Leave Out</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Real passages usually contain more than the argument. They contain
        set-up, examples, repetition, emotional emphasis, jokes, quotations,
        and background. Some of that material may be useful for understanding
        the passage, but not all of it belongs in the reconstruction.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-background-information">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <term>Background information</term> is material that helps orient
          the reader but does not directly support the conclusion.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-reconstruction-filter">
      <title>The reconstruction filter</title>
      <p>
        When deciding whether to include a sentence, ask: does this claim
        help support the conclusion, or does it merely help the reader
        understand the topic? If it supports the conclusion, include it.
        If it just sets the scene, leave it out of the reconstruction.
      </p>
      <p>
        Leaving something out is not the same as saying it is unimportant.
        A sentence can be rhetorically important, historically interesting,
        or emotionally powerful without functioning as a premise. Logic is
        concerned with the support relation. We reconstruct that relation.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <example xml:id="ex-city-hall-background">
      <title>Background and argument</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Passage:
        </p>
        <p>
          <q>The old city hall was built in 1894, and its council chamber
          still has the original carved oak benches. The city should move
          public hearings to an accessible building until the elevator is
          repaired. Residents who use wheelchairs cannot reach the current
          chamber, and public hearings should be held where residents can
          actually participate.</q>
        </p>
        <p>
          Reconstruction:
        </p>
        <p>
          P1: Residents who use wheelchairs cannot reach the current
          council chamber.
        </p>
        <p>
          P2: Public hearings should be held where residents can actually
          participate.
        </p>
        <p>
          C: The city should move public hearings to an accessible building
          until the elevator is repaired. (from P1 and P2, which are
          dependent)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      The age of city hall and the carved oak benches do not belong in the
      reconstruction. They may make the passage more vivid, but they do
      not support the conclusion. The two access-centered claims do.
      Together they explain why the location of public hearings matters.
    </p>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-repetition">
      <title>Repetition and compression</title>
      <p>
        Sometimes a passage states the same reason more than once. In a
        reconstruction, repeated material can often be compressed into a
        single premise. Suppose an author writes: <q>The system is too
        complicated. Ordinary people cannot understand it. The paperwork
        is confusing even for experts.</q> In a reconstruction, that might
        become one premise: <q>The system is too complicated for ordinary
        people to navigate.</q> That is not cheating. It is what a good
        reconstruction does: it gives us the argument without making us
        trip over every bit of prose.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-dependent-independent-support">
    <title>Dependent and Independent Support</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Not all premises support a conclusion in the same way. Sometimes
        each premise gives its own reason to accept the conclusion.
        Sometimes two or more premises have to work together. This
        distinction matters both for reconstruction and for criticism:
        it tells us how important each premise is to the argument.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-independent-support">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Premises give <term>independent support</term> when each premise
          gives some reason to accept the conclusion on its own, without
          needing to be combined with another premise.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-dependent-support">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A premise gives <term>dependent support</term> when the support
          it gives for a conclusion would be weaker without one or more
          other premises on which it depends.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-independent-significance">
      <title>Why the distinction matters</title>
      <p>
        The independent/dependent distinction helps us understand the
        significance of a premise. If a premise gives independent support,
        then removing it may weaken the argument without destroying the
        whole line of reasoning. If a premise is part of a dependent set,
        then removing it may break that line of reasoning entirely.
      </p>
      <p>
        Think of two ways to support a shelf. Independent support is like
        two separate brackets: each one helps hold the shelf up. Dependent
        support is like a bracket and the screws that attach it to the
        wall: neither does the job by itself in the same way. In arguments,
        dependent premises are often a fact plus a principle, a conditional
        plus its antecedent, or a general claim plus a particular case.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <example xml:id="ex-independent-support">
      <title>Independent support</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Passage:
        </p>
        <p>
          <q>You should take the early bus. It is usually less crowded.
          Also, the early bus gets to campus before the coffee line gets
          ridiculous.</q>
        </p>
        <p>
          Reconstruction:
        </p>
        <p>P1: The early bus is usually less crowded.</p>
        <p>
          P2: The early bus gets to campus before the coffee line gets
          ridiculous.
        </p>
        <p>C: You should take the early bus. (from P1 and P2 independently)</p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      Either premise gives some reason to take the early bus. If P2 turns
      out false, P1 still gives support. If P1 turns out false, P2 still
      gives support. That is independent support.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-dependent-support">
      <title>Dependent support</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Passage:
        </p>
        <p>
          <q>If the only available exam time conflicts with a required lab,
          the department should offer a make-up exam. The only available
          exam time conflicts with a required lab. So the department should
          offer a make-up exam.</q>
        </p>
        <p>
          Reconstruction:
        </p>
        <p>
          P1: If the only available exam time conflicts with a required lab,
          the department should offer a make-up exam.
        </p>
        <p>
          P2: The only available exam time conflicts with a required lab.
        </p>
        <p>
          C: The department should offer a make-up exam. (from P1 and P2,
          which are dependent)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      P1 alone does not show that the department should offer a make-up
      exam, because it does not say the condition has actually been met.
      P2 alone does not show it either, because it does not state the
      policy principle. Together they do the work.
    </p>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-accessible-diagram-rule">
      <title>The verbal diagram rule</title>
      <p>
        Diagrams are helpful for many students, but the information in a
        diagram must also be stated in words. A reconstruction is not
        complete unless each conclusion says which earlier claims support
        it and whether that support is dependent or independent.
      </p>
      <p>
        The parenthetical note is the accessible version of the diagram.
        It should be clear enough that a reader who never sees the arrows
        still knows the structure of the argument.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-subconclusions-layered-arguments">
    <title>Sub-Conclusions and Layered Arguments</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Many arguments do not move directly from premises to one final
        conclusion. They build. A premise supports an intermediate claim;
        that intermediate claim then supports a further claim. Chapter 1
        introduced these intermediate claims as sub-conclusions. Now we
        use them in reconstruction.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-sub-conclusion-ch2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>sub-conclusion</term> is a claim that is supported by
          earlier premises and then functions as support for a later
          conclusion.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-layered-labels">
      <title>Labels for layers</title>
      <p>
        When an argument has layers, label the intermediate conclusions
        C1, C2, and so on. The final conclusion can be labeled C or the
        last numbered conclusion. What matters is consistency: the labels
        in the reconstruction and any diagram or explanation must match.
      </p>
      <p>
        Every conclusion, including every sub-conclusion, should include
        a note saying what it follows from. That note is not busywork.
        It is the argument structure.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <example xml:id="ex-food-pantry-layered">
      <title>A layered argument</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Passage:
        </p>
        <p>
          <q>You should donate to the campus food pantry. It buys staple
          foods in bulk, so each dollar goes farther than it would at a
          grocery store. It also lets students choose what they need,
          which respects their dignity and reduces waste. Programs that
          use money efficiently and respect the people they serve deserve
          support.</q>
        </p>
        <p>
          Reconstruction:
        </p>
        <p>
          P1: The campus food pantry buys staple foods in bulk.
        </p>
        <p>
          C1: Each dollar donated to the campus food pantry goes farther
          than it would at a grocery store. (from P1)
        </p>
        <p>
          P2: The campus food pantry lets students choose what they need.
        </p>
        <p>
          C2: The campus food pantry respects students' dignity and reduces
          waste. (from P2)
        </p>
        <p>
          P3: Programs that use money efficiently and respect the people
          they serve deserve support.
        </p>
        <p>
          C: You should donate to the campus food pantry. (from C1, C2,
          and P3, which are dependent)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      The final inference depends on all three pieces. C1 gives the
      efficiency claim. C2 gives the dignity-and-waste claim. P3 supplies
      the general principle connecting those features to the practical
      conclusion. If one of those pieces is missing, the final support is
      weaker or incomplete.
    </p>

    <p>
      The food pantry was a fresh passage. We saw another layered
      argument earlier, in <xref ref="sec-recognizing-arguments"/>: the
      paragraph about donating to Oxfam. The reconstruction we produced
      there was a good first pass — built with the extraction tools of
      Chapter 1, not the more careful machinery of this chapter. The
      tools we've worked through here let us revisit it: ask whether
      each support relation is dependent or independent, identify any
      implicit premises the Chapter 1 version absorbed quietly, and
      reconsider whether every sentence in the original passage was
      doing argumentative work. We'll do that revisit in the
      end-of-chapter exercises.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-implicit-premises">
    <title>Implicit Premises</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Ordinary arguments often leave things unsaid. Sometimes that is
        harmless. We do not state every background assumption in every
        conversation, because conversation would become unbearable. But
        in reconstruction, an unstated assumption may need to be made
        explicit.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-implicit-premise">
      <statement>
        <p>
          An <term>implicit premise</term> is an unstated claim that must
          be supplied to make an argument's reasoning explicit.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-implicit-limits">
      <title>When to add one</title>
      <p>
        Adding an implicit premise is a judgment call, and three things
        make the judgment a reasonable one. The argument needs the
        claim — without it, the support relation falls apart, and the
        argument as written makes a leap that isn't actually there on
        the page. The claim has to be one the arguer would accept on
        reflection, not a brand-new principle they were never committed
        to; the prose left the claim implicit because the author
        thought it obvious, not because the author would deny it if
        pressed. And the wording stays minimal. An implicit premise is
        meant to make the existing argument explicit. It is not an
        excuse to import a fresh line of thought.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <example xml:id="ex-implicit-premise">
      <title>A modest implicit premise</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Passage:
        </p>
        <p>
          <q>The university should keep the shuttle running after evening
          classes. Some students have required labs that end after dark.</q>
        </p>
        <p>
          Reconstruction:
        </p>
        <p>
          P1: Some students have required labs that end after dark.
        </p>
        <p>
          P2: The university should provide safe transportation options for
          students whose required classes end after dark. (implicit)
        </p>
        <p>
          C: The university should keep the shuttle running after evening
          classes. (from P1 and P2, which are dependent)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      P2 is not stated, but it is a natural assumption behind the argument.
      Without it, P1 gives us a fact about students' schedules but not yet
      a reason for the shuttle policy. With it, the support relation is
      explicit.
    </p>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-overcharity">
      <title>Do not over-reconstruct</title>
      <p>
        The danger is overcharity. Suppose someone says, <q>We should ban
        all phones from campus because phones are distracting.</q> It would
        be unfair to reconstruct the argument as if the author had also
        argued that phone bans improve mental health, increase friendship,
        reduce cheating, and restore civic life. Maybe those claims are
        relevant. Maybe they are even true. But they are not in the
        argument unless the passage gives us reason to attribute them to
        the arguer.
      </p>
      <p>
        A good implicit premise makes the existing argument explicit. It
        does not replace the existing argument with a better one.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-longer-passages">
    <title>Reconstructing Longer Passages</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Longer passages are where reconstruction becomes genuinely useful.
        They also require patience. A long passage may contain background,
        examples, multiple arguments, explanations, objections, and side
        comments. The job is to find the argument that matters and represent
        it clearly.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-longer-method">
      <title>A working method</title>
      <p>
        The five-step procedure from Chapter 1 was for picking an
        argument out of prose. Reconstructing a long passage takes
        more than that. Use this expanded procedure as a first pass
        through any passage that runs more than a paragraph or two.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Find the final conclusion.</alert> Ask: what is the
            author trying to get me to accept by the end of the
            passage? On a long passage this can take two reads. The
            conclusion is not always where the author put the most
            rhetorical weight; sometimes the most quotable line is
            doing emotional work while the actual conclusion sits in
            a quieter sentence near the start or end.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Gather the claims that seem to support the
            conclusion.</alert> Don't worry yet about which are
            premises and which are sub-conclusions, or about ordering.
            Just list the candidates.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Remove background, examples, repetition, and
            rhetorical decoration</alert> unless they function as
            premises. Vivid imagery and historical context can make a
            passage compelling without supporting the conclusion. A
            useful test: if removing a sentence leaves the support
            relation untouched, the sentence was decoration, not
            argument.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Look for sub-conclusions.</alert> Some of the
            claims you gathered will turn out to be supported by
            other claims you gathered. When you find one, label it
            C1 (or C2, etc.) and note what supports it.
            Sub-conclusions are common in real arguments; on any
            passage longer than a few sentences, assume there is at
            least one and look for it.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Add modest implicit premises only when needed.</alert>
            If the support relation has a hole and the missing piece
            is something the arguer plainly assumes, supply it and
            label it as implicit. If the missing piece is a
            brand-new line of argument, don't.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Write the reconstruction with support notes after
            every conclusion.</alert> <em>(from P1 and P2,
            dependent)</em>, <em>(from C1 alone)</em>, and so on.
            Without those notes, a reconstruction is just a list of
            claims. With them, it's an argument structure a reader
            can examine, criticize, and learn from.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </paragraphs>

    <example xml:id="ex-long-reconstruction">
      <title>A longer reconstruction</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Passage:
        </p>
        <p>
          <q>We should not institute a moratorium on data centers. New
          data centers are 3-10 times more efficient from a property tax
          standpoint than the next best developments. Property taxes pay
          for schools, which are already underfunded. New data centers are
          our best hope for fully funded schools. And they provide some
          decent construction jobs in the short term and tech industry jobs
          in the longer term. Environmental concerns are real, but
          overblown. Data centers consume only around 5% of US electricity.
          From what you hear, you'd think it was 50%.</q>
        </p>
        <p>
          Reconstruction:
        </p>
        <p>
          P1: New data centers are 3-10 times more efficient from a
          property tax standpoint than the next best developments.
        </p>
        <p>
          P2: Property taxes pay for schools.
        </p>
        <p>
          P3: Schools are already underfunded.
        </p>
        <p>
          C1: New data centers are our best hope for fully funded schools.
          (from P1, P2, and P3, which are dependent)
        </p>
        <p>
          P4: New data centers provide decent construction jobs in the
          short term.
        </p>
        <p>
          P5: New data centers provide tech industry jobs in the longer
          term.
        </p>
        <p>
          C2: New data centers provide economic benefits. (from P4 and P5
          independently)
        </p>
        <p>
          P6: Data centers consume only around 5% of US electricity.
        </p>
        <p>
          P7: Public discussion can make data centers sound as if they
          consume far more electricity than they do.
        </p>
        <p>
          C3: The environmental concerns about data centers are real, but
          overblown. (from P6 and P7, which are dependent)
        </p>
        <p>
          C: We should not institute a moratorium on data centers. (from
          C1 and C2 independently; C3 supports C by answering an objection)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      This reconstruction does not preserve every sentence exactly as
      written. It organizes the reasoning. It also shows why each premise
      matters. P1, P2, and P3 work together to support C1: the tax
      efficiency of data centers matters because schools need property tax
      revenue. P4 and P5 each give some support for C2, since short-term
      construction jobs and longer-term tech jobs are separate economic
      benefits. C3 is slightly different. It responds to an objection
      rather than giving the main positive reason for the conclusion. In a
      longer reconstruction, that matters: some claims build the case
      directly, while others defend it against an expected challenge.
    </p>

  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch2">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter developed argument reconstruction as a close-reading
      skill. The core ideas, section by section:
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>From Standard Form to Reconstruction (§2.1).</alert>
      Reconstruction is a cleaned-up representation of an argument. It
      identifies premises, conclusions, and support relations. It is not
      a transcript and not an excuse to invent a better argument. Charity
      requires us to represent the strongest reasonable version of the
      argument the author can fairly be understood as giving.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>What to Include, What to Leave Out (§2.2).</alert>
      Not every sentence in a passage belongs in the reconstruction.
      Background, repetition, examples, and rhetorical decoration may help
      the passage work as prose without functioning as premises.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Dependent and Independent Support (§2.3).</alert>
      Independent premises each give support on their own. A premise is
      dependent when the support it gives would be weaker without another
      premise on which it depends. The distinction helps us understand the
      significance of each premise: removing a dependent premise may break
      a line of support, while removing an independent premise may merely
      weaken it.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Sub-Conclusions and Layered Arguments (§2.4).</alert>
      A sub-conclusion is supported by earlier premises and then serves as
      support for a later conclusion. Every conclusion and sub-conclusion
      should say what it follows from.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Implicit Premises (§2.5).</alert>
      Ordinary arguments often leave assumptions unstated. Add an implicit
      premise only when the argument needs it, the arguer is reasonably
      committed to it, and the wording can be kept minimal.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Reconstructing Longer Passages (§2.6).</alert>
      Longer passages require a method: find the final conclusion, list
      support claims, remove clutter, identify sub-conclusions, add modest
      implicit premises when needed, and write support notes after every
      conclusion.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch2-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch2-argument-reconstruction">
        <title>Argument reconstruction</title>
        <p>A cleaned-up representation of an argument that identifies its premises, conclusion or conclusions, and support relations. (§2.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch2-background-information">
        <title>Background information</title>
        <p>Material that helps orient the reader but does not directly support the conclusion. (§2.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch2-dependent-support">
        <title>Dependent support</title>
        <p>A support relation in which the support a premise gives for a conclusion would be weaker without one or more other premises on which it depends. (§2.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch2-implicit-premise">
        <title>Implicit premise</title>
        <p>An unstated claim that must be supplied to make an argument's reasoning explicit. (§2.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch2-independent-support">
        <title>Independent support</title>
        <p>A support relation in which each premise gives some reason to accept the conclusion on its own, without needing to be combined with another premise. (§2.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch2-principle-of-charity">
        <title>Principle of charity</title>
        <p>The norm of interpreting an argument in the strongest reasonable way consistent with what the arguer actually says and seems committed to. (§2.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch2-sub-conclusion">
        <title>Sub-conclusion</title>
        <p>A claim that is supported by earlier premises and then functions as support for a later conclusion. (§2.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch2-support-note">
        <title>Support note</title>
        <p>A parenthetical note after a conclusion that states which earlier claims support it and whether the support is dependent or independent. (§2.3)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch2">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch2-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Basic Reconstruction</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each passage, reconstruct the argument in standard form.
          Include a support note after the conclusion.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s01-01">
        <statement>
          <p>The city should add more crosswalks near campus. Students cross those streets constantly, and drivers often fail to slow down at the current crossings.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s01-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The cafeteria should keep one station open later. Evening labs end after the main dinner period, and students in those labs still need a real meal.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s01-03">
        <statement>
          <p>Do not rely on that weather app today. It has been wrong three days in a row, and the local forecast gives a different prediction.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch2-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Include or Omit</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each passage, identify the final conclusion, the premises
          that belong in the reconstruction, and any material that should
          be omitted as background or rhetorical decoration.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s02-01">
        <statement>
          <p>The train station opened in 1910 and still has its original tile floor. The city should repair it rather than replace it. The building is historically significant, and repairing it would cost less than constructing a new station.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s02-02">
        <statement>
          <p>Everyone loves a dramatic classroom demonstration. Still, the chemistry department should replace the old fume hoods. The current hoods fail inspection too often, and failed hoods expose students to unnecessary risk.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch2-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Dependent and Independent Support</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Reconstruct each argument and indicate whether the support is
          dependent, independent, or mixed.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s03-01">
        <statement>
          <p>If the archive closes before noon, researchers who travel from out of town cannot finish their work. The archive closes before noon on Fridays. So out-of-town researchers cannot finish their work on Fridays.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s03-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The new advising system should be changed. It crashes during registration week. It also hides degree requirements behind too many menus.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s03-03">
        <statement>
          <p>The university should keep the writing center funded. Students who use it revise more effectively, and programs that improve student writing deserve stable funding. The center also gives peer tutors valuable teaching experience.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch2-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Sub-Conclusions</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Reconstruct each passage using sub-conclusions where appropriate.
          Every conclusion must say what it follows from.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s04-01">
        <statement>
          <p>The discount brings in students who would otherwise skip the museum, and those students often return later with family members. That means the student discount builds future audiences. Programs that build future audiences are worth preserving, so the museum has a good reason to continue the discount.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s04-02">
        <statement>
          <p>Street trees reduce summer temperatures on sidewalks. Cooler sidewalks make downtown more usable during the hottest months. The trees also absorb stormwater, which helps reduce flooding after heavy rain. Downtown will be more livable if the city plants more street trees.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch2-s05">
      <title>Exercise Set 5: Implicit Premises</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Reconstruct each argument. If an implicit premise is needed,
          include it and label it as implicit.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s05-01">
        <statement>
          <p>A few hundred dollars can be the difference between a student staying enrolled and dropping out. The emergency grant program gives students that kind of short-term help. The program protects student retention.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s05-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The student body has changed significantly since the survey was conducted. Old survey results are a poor guide to what current students need.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch2-s06">
      <title>Exercise Set 6: Longer Passage Reconstruction</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Reconstruct the argument in each passage. Some statements may
          not be necessary. There may be implicit premises or
          sub-conclusions. If you use a diagram, the prose reconstruction
          must still state all support relations.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s06-01">
        <statement>
          <p>The new bus app is convenient for many riders, and it may reduce lines at the station. But some riders do not own smartphones, and others have limited data plans. A public transit system that makes access depend on owning a particular device or paying for a particular service excludes some of the people it is supposed to serve. The city can still encourage the app while keeping cash and card payment available on buses. So the app can be useful without becoming the only way to buy a ticket.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s06-02">
        <statement>
          <p>Automated tutors can answer routine questions quickly, and that is useful. But students often come to office hours because they are confused about what they are confused about. In those cases, a human instructor can listen, ask follow-up questions, and notice patterns the student cannot yet name. The hardest learning problems often require that kind of diagnosis. Automated tutors are useful supplements, but they are not replacements for office hours.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch2-s07">
      <title>Exercise Set 7: Revisiting a Chapter 1 Reconstruction</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Reconstruction is a draft skill: a first reconstruction can
          be improved by going back over it with sharper tools. This
          exercise asks you to do exactly that.
        </p>
        <p>
          Below is the original passage from
          <xref ref="sec-recognizing-arguments"/> about donating to
          Oxfam, followed by the reconstruction we produced there.
          Apply the tools of this chapter to that reconstruction.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch2-s07-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <em>Original passage:</em>
          </p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              You should donate to Oxfam. Oxfam efficiently uses
              contributions to help end long-term poverty by providing
              the tools for people to get an education and support
              their families. Eighty-nine cents of every dollar goes
              directly to organizations on the ground. The aid
              provides for things like goats and schoolbooks, so that
              a family can provide for itself and the next generation
              has options. Also, it feels good to help people.
            </p>
          </blockquote>
          <p>
            <em>Reconstruction from <xref ref="sec-recognizing-arguments"/>:</em>
          </p>
          <p>P1: 89 cents of every dollar goes directly to organizations on the ground.</p>
          <p>P2: The aid provides for things like goats and schoolbooks.</p>
          <p>C1: The aid Oxfam provides makes it so a family can provide for itself and the next generation has options. <em>(from P2)</em></p>
          <p>C2: Oxfam efficiently uses contributions to help end long-term poverty by providing the tools for people to get an education and support their families. <em>(from P1 and C1)</em></p>
          <p>P3: It feels good to help people.</p>
          <p>C3: You should donate to Oxfam. <em>(from C2 and P3)</em></p>
          <p>
            Now answer the following:
          </p>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <p>
                For each support note in the reconstruction, decide
                whether the support is dependent or independent. Rewrite
                each support note so that the answer is included.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Identify at least one implicit premise that the original
                Chapter 1 reconstruction absorbed quietly. Where in the
                reasoning does it belong? Write it out.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Reconsider every sentence in the original passage. Is
                any sentence doing background, rhetorical, or emotional
                work rather than supporting the conclusion? If so, name
                it and say what kind of work it's doing.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write two or three sentences explaining what the tools
                of this chapter added to the original reconstruction.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
